      • setDescription

        public void setDescription​(java.lang.String description)
        Sets a description of this resource reference. Corresponds to the description element within resource-ref in the deployment descriptor.
        Parameters:
        description - a textual description of this resource reference
        See Also:
        Servlet 4.0 Specification, Section 14.4.3: Resource References

      • setName

        public void setName​(java.lang.String name)
        Sets the name of this resource reference. Corresponds to the res-ref-name element in the deployment descriptor.

        The name is relative to the java:comp/env context. For example, a name of jdbc/MyDataSource would be accessible as java:comp/env/jdbc/MyDataSource.

        Parameters:
        name - the resource reference name
        See Also:
        Servlet 4.0 Specification, Section 14.4.3: Resource References

      • getName

        public java.lang.String getName()
        Returns the name of this resource reference.
        Returns:
        the resource reference name

      • setClassName

        public void setClassName​(java.lang.String className)
        Sets the expected Java type of the referenced resource. Corresponds to the res-type element in the deployment descriptor.

        This must be a fully-qualified class name. For a JDBC data source, this would typically be javax.sql.DataSource.

        Parameters:
        className - the fully-qualified class name of the resource type
        See Also:
        Servlet 4.0 Specification, Section 14.4.3: Resource References

      • setResAuth

        public void setResAuth​(javax.annotation.Resource.AuthenticationType resAuth)
        Sets the authentication type for this resource. Corresponds to the res-auth element in the deployment descriptor.

        CONTAINER indicates that the container will sign on to the resource manager on behalf of the web application. APPLICATION indicates that the application will sign on programmatically.

        Parameters:
        resAuth - the authentication type
        See Also:
        Resource.AuthenticationType.CONTAINER, Resource.AuthenticationType.APPLICATION, Servlet 4.0 Specification, Section 14.4.3: Resource References

      • setResSharingScope

        public void setResSharingScope​(java.lang.String resSharingScope)
        Sets the sharing scope for connections to this resource. Corresponds to the res-sharing-scope element in the deployment descriptor.

        Valid values are Shareable (default) or Unshareable. Shareable means connections obtained from the resource can be shared by multiple components. Unshareable means connections are not shared.

        Parameters:
        resSharingScope - the sharing scope (Shareable or Unshareable)
        See Also:
        Servlet 4.0 Specification, Section 14.4.3: Resource References
